article.headline: Schonrock perfect (and one) behind the arc
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Purdue coach Kristy Curry hoped her team
learned its lesson after watching Shannon Schonrock hit seven
3-pointers in a loss to Minnesota in January. Evidently not.

Schonrock hit all four of her 3-pointers to help No. 12
Minnesota bounce back from a demoralizing loss and beat Purdue
71-49 on Sunday.

"We left her. That's effort, mentally and physically and
understanding that your actions have consequences," an exasperated
Curry said. "You can't help off Shannon. She always shoots really
well against us."

Sunday was no different. Schonrock got going when she hit a
3-pointer from the corner and was fouled by Brina Pollack. She
converted the rare four-point play to give the Gophers a 13-4 lead
with under 9 minutes to go in the first half, and the rout was on.

Schonrock finished with 13 points. Shannon Bolden chipped in 10
points for Minnesota (19-5, 9-3 Big Ten) and played her usual
stellar defense on Purdue guard Katie Gearlds, who managed just
seven points on 3-of-9 shooting.

Lindsay Wisdom-Hylton had 13 points and six rebounds to lead
Purdue (13-10, 6-6).

After shooting 0-for-17 from 3-point range in a 31-point home
loss to ninth-ranked Michigan State on Thursday, the Gophers came
out determined to take the ball to the basket on Sunday.

They opened a quick 8-2 lead on four drives to the basket and
used a much improved defensive effort to fluster the Boilermakers.

"They were probably really upset," Curry said. "I'm sure it
hasn't been a fun couple of days here. We should match that same
kind of intensity."

Purdue turned the ball over 10 times in their first 13
possessions, including three traveling violations and a double
dribble. The Boilermakers didn't crack double digits until 14
minutes had passed in the first half, and committed 24 turnovers in
the game.

"We have to be willing to accept responsibility for our
actions," Curry said. "We looked really, really young."

Minnesota's aggressive play on offense eventually opened things
up on the perimeter for Schonrock.

Reduced to tears over her 0-for-7 shooting from behind the arc
against Michigan State, Schonrock was all smiles against the
Boilermakers.

She buried all three of her 3-pointers in the first half,
including the four-point play, to lead the Gophers to a 36-18 lead
at halftime.

"I just had to think of it as one game," Schonrock said of her
struggles against the Spartans. "A shooter just has to keep
shooting to get yourself out of it."

It was a familiar sight for the Boilermakers, who watched
Schonrock score a career-high 25 points in a 20-point loss in West
Lafayette, Ind., on Jan. 13.

Once again, Purdue couldn't keep up with the sharp-shooting
point guard.

"I really don't know what it is against them," Schonrock said.
"I just got some good screens and got open."

The Boilermakers shot just 33 percent and committed 15 turnovers
in the first half to dig a big hole.

Compounding Purdue's problems, leading scorer Erin Lawless came
up with a gimpy elbow after a fall midway through the first half
and scored just 11 points.

The Boilermakers were able to close the gap with an 11-3 run
midway through the second half. Wisdom-Hylton capped the spurt with
a layup that made the score 49-33.

But the Gophers came right back with six straight points, four
by Janel McCarville, to push the lead back to a comfortable 22
points.

McCarville had eight points, 12 rebounds and seven assists for
the Gophers, who beat Purdue in both games in a season for the
first time since 1984-85.
